{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Authenticated identity â€” git-bug-model identity entity + SSHSIG signing + Jira accountId mapping\n\n## Context\n\nrebar has no real concept of **identity** for the user running it. `COMMENT.author`,\n`CREATE.assignee`, and `claim --assignee` are unauthenticated free strings resolved (at best)\nfrom `git config user.name`; anyone with push access to `origin/tickets` can forge any author,\nand replay trusts the bytes. This epic gives rebar a first-class, optionally-authenticated\nidentity so projects can (1) **sync to Jira (and later GitHub Issues) with users that correctly\nmap to external user objects**, (2) **optionally require an authenticated identity** that\nattributes ticket changes to a real person (defaulting to the GitHub user who commits), while\n(3) projects that don't opt in need **no authentication setup at all** (low-friction default).\n\nThis plan was selected after a wide survey of OSS ticket systems (git-bug, Radicle/Heartwood,\nPijul, Keybase, TUF, Sigstore, Fossil, Plane, Huly, OpenProject, Taiga, sourcehut, Bugzilla,\nGitLab/Gitea/Forgejo) and the git/GitHub/SSH/Jira tooling landscape. Full decision trail +\nresearch citations live in the brainstorm session log.\n\n## The chosen pattern â€” adopt git-bug's model wholesale, fill its gaps\n\ngit-bug is the strongest analog to rebar (event-sourced, git-backed, multi-clone). Its identity\nmodel is the parity target and maps 1:1 onto rebar's existing event/ticket machinery:\n\n- **Identity = a first-class versioned entity.** In rebar, a new `identity` ticket type (the\n  `session_log` precedent), whose **event log IS the version chain** â€” so rotation, convergence,\n  and sync come for free from machinery rebar already has.\n- **Stable id from a self-certifying genesis** (TOFU): the genesis version embeds the first\n  public key; the identity's stable id derives from it.\n- **Authors referenced by a stable id-stub**; events ALSO carry denormalized `name`/`email`\n  for offline readability and convergence (Fossil's \"U-card\" denormalization â€” no cross-entity\n  FK needed to replay an event).\n- **Optional detached signature** over each event's canonical bytes; **in-band public keys**\n  on the identity make verification **offline** with no network dependency.\n- **Key rotation** via the version chain (git-bug's `ValidKeysAtTime`, Lamport-scoped).\n- **External mapping via immutable metadata** (`github-login`, `jira-accountId`) with\n  **resolve-or-create + ghost identities** on bridge import.\n\nThis is **one coherent pattern in one trust family** (self-managed keys + TOFU + offline). The\nonly deltas from vanilla git-bug are gap-fills that are either *completing git-bug's own\nunfinished work* or *rebar-platform integration* â€” none import a foreign trust model:\n\n- **G1 â€” SSHSIG instead of PGP.** git-bug signs with OpenPGP (near-zero real-world adoption).\n  We sign with **SSHSIG** (`ssh-keygen -Y sign/-Y verify`, namespace `rebar`) over the event's\n  canonical bytes, reusing the SSH key developers already have registered on GitHub. This is a\n  drop-in primitive substitution (both are \"detached sig over canonical bytes + in-band pubkey\")\n  justified by adoption and by the GitHub-default-identity goal. No maintained pure-Python SSHSIG\n  verifier exists, so shell out to `ssh-keygen -Y verify`; keep `cryptography` available for\n  raw ed25519 / OpenSSH key parsing if we later drop the subprocess.\n- **G2 â€” Signed identity-chain authorization (the layer git-bug stubbed).** git-bug's\n  `IsProtected()` is an unimplemented TODO, so anyone can append an identity version adding their\n  own key. We **implement it**: an identity version that adds/rotates/revokes a key must be\n  **signed by a currently-valid key for that identity** (per-person **1-of-n** multi-device,\n  Keybase's topology â€” NOT Radicle's per-repo m-of-n governance, which is the wrong scope).\n- **G3 â€” Project-level enforcement policy.** git-bug signing is per-user opt-in with no project\n  gate. We add an opt-in **local write-gate** (refuse to author a mutating event unsigned on\n  opt-in machines) + **CI/`fsck` verification** that flags any event lacking a valid signature\n  from a known identity. Mirrors rebar's existing close-gate enforcement shape.\n- **G4 â€” Availability adaptation.** git-bug REJECTS at replay on a bad signature. rebar's\n  invariant is **replay NEVER rejects** (one bad push must not wedge a clone): verification only\n  **marks** events `verified|unverified|unsigned` and CI fails the policy; replay always accepts.\n- **G6 â€” Compaction survival.** rebar compaction folds N events into a SNAPSHOT storing only\n  `source_event_uuids` + `compiled_state`, losing per-event identity/signature. The SNAPSHOT\n  payload + `process_snapshot` must **carry/surface folded-event identity + signatures** so\n  verification reads back through compaction.\n\n**Deliberately OUT (de-frankensteining):** no DSSE/Sigstore/keyless seam (a different,\nonline/CA/OIDC trust model incompatible with our offline/TOFU one â€” pure speculative YAGNI; the\ncanonical-bytes boundary already preserves the option). No active GitHub `ssh_signing_keys`\ncross-check (\"social proof\") in v1 â€” `github-login` is stored as plain metadata; the active\nproof is a labeled follow-on. (See `e68d`'s sibling security epic `8a1c` for the cryptographic\nhardening / standard-attestation follow-ons.)\n\n## Three trust tiers (one ladder, one trust model)\n\n- **Tier 0 â€” unverified (default, zero-config):** author = `git config user.name`/`user.email`,\n  denormalized onto the event. DCO-`Signed-off-by`-style; forgeable; no auth setup required.\n- **Tier 1 â€” SSH-signed (opt-in):** event canonical bytes signed via SSHSIG with the dev's\n  existing key; in-band pubkey on the identity; verified offline. Binds event â†’ key â†’ identity.\n\n## Jira identity integration (what we need + how, given ACLI)\n\n**The identity entity IS the local-identity â†’ Jira `accountId` map** the reconciler needs. The\nJira CLI/REST research is unambiguous that a sync tool **must maintain its own map** rather than\nresolve per-write, because `accountId` is the only stable id, **email is privacy-gated (often\n`null`)**, and `GET /user/search` is prefix-match (unreliable/ambiguous). git-bug's\nbridge-metadata pattern gives us exactly this: store `jira-accountId` (+ `email`) as immutable\nidentity metadata, cached and authoritative; use `/user/search` only to **bootstrap/repair** the\nmap, not on the per-write path.\n\nHow rebar talks to Jira today (`src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/`):\n- **Official `acli jira workitem â€¦`** via subprocess (`acli_subprocess.py`, `acli_cli_ops.py`)\n  for create/edit/transition/comment/search/get.\n- **Direct REST** (`acli_rest.py`, urllib + Basic auth) for what acli can't do (assignee ops,\n  issue properties, transitions, reparenting).\n- Auth: `JIRA_URL`/`JIRA_USER`/`JIRA_PROJECT` (env or config) + `JIRA_API_TOKEN` (env-only).\n- Today only **assignee** syncs (bidirectional, bare string; outbound resolves an accountId via\n  `/user/assignable/search`, inbound stores displayName). **No reporter/creator sync, no\n  per-user binding** (`binding_store.py` is ticketâ†”jira-key only).\n\nACLI constraints that shape the design:\n- Official acli has **no user-lookup command** and **no `--reporter` flag**; its `--assignee`\n  accepts an **email or accountId** and resolves server-side (fine for assignee on create/edit).\n- **Reporter attribution requires direct REST** (`fields.reporter:{accountId}` on create) **and\n  the \"Modify Reporter\" project permission** â€” without it, reporter is forced to the\n  authenticating (bot) account regardless of tool. This is the central constraint on \"attribute\n  ticket changes to a user\": assignee is achievable via acli; faithful reporter attribution\n  needs REST + that permission, and degrades to the bot account otherwise.\n\nIntegration design:\n- **Outbound:** resolve a rebar author/assignee â†’ their `identity` â†’ `jira-accountId`; set\n  **assignee** (acli `--assignee` by accountId, or REST `PUT /issue/{key}/assignee`) and\n  **reporter** (REST `fields.reporter`, when Modify Reporter is granted). On a missing mapping,\n  bootstrap via `/user/search` by email and **cache the accountId onto the identity**; if email\n  is hidden/unmatched, **degrade gracefully** to `-1` (project default assignee) / unassigned /\n  bot-reporter, never hard-fail.\n- **Inbound:** Jira `{accountId, displayName, emailAddress}` â†’ reverse-resolve the rebar identity\n  by `accountId`; **resolve-or-create a ghost identity** (git-bug pattern) when unmapped, keyed\n  by accountId, so attribution is preserved and auto-upgrades when the person later registers.\n- **Provider-neutral:** key external mapping on the provider's stable id (`jira-accountId` now,\n  GitHub node-id later â€” never email), so the same identity carries multiple `{provider:\n  external_id}` mappings and the GitHub-Issues-sync epic (`be74`) reuses it directly.\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- A user running rebar has a modeled identity; ticket events attribute to it (Tier 0 with zero\n  config; Tier 1 cryptographically when opted in).\n- An opt-in project can REQUIRE an authenticated identity: opt-in machines refuse to author\n  unsigned mutating events, and CI/`fsck` flags any unsigned/unknown-author event in the merged\n  log â€” while replay never rejects (availability preserved).\n- The `identity` entity provides a stable localâ†”Jira `accountId` mapping that the reconciler uses\n  to attribute Jira assignee (and reporter, where permission allows), with graceful degradation\n  when an accountId can't be resolved; unmapped inbound Jira users become auto-upgrading ghosts.\n- Default install experience is unchanged; signing and enforcement are fully opt-in.\n- Key rotation works (old events still verify against their era's keys); a folded (compacted)\n  signed event still verifies through the SNAPSHOT.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] `identity` first-class ticket type: versioned (event-log-as-version-chain), stable\n      self-certifying genesis id, in-band public keys, immutable external-mapping metadata\n      (`jira-accountId`, `github-login`), gate-/lifecycle-handling appropriate to a non-work type.\n- [ ] Author reference on events: denormalized `name`/`email` always present (Tier 0) + stable\n      `author_id` + optional `sig`; resolves author from `git config` at write time. Backward-\n      compatible event-schema additions (existing free-string authors continue to replay).\n- [ ] Tier-1 SSHSIG signing over each event's `canonical_bytes` (namespace `rebar`), reusing the\n      developer's SSH key (ssh-agent supported); verify via `ssh-keygen -Y verify`, offline,\n      against in-band identity keys.\n- [ ] G2: signed identity-chain authorization â€” key add/rotate/revoke versions must be signed by\n      a currently-valid key for that identity (per-person 1-of-n); equivocation/forks flagged.\n- [ ] G3: opt-in project config (`identity.require_authenticated` or similar) â†’ local write-gate\n      (fail-closed on unsigned authoring) + `rebar verify-identity`/`fsck` + CI check over the\n      merged log. `--force`-style override with recorded justification.\n- [ ] G4: replay NEVER rejects; `show`/`fsck` surface `verified|unverified|unsigned`; a bad push\n      cannot wedge a clone.\n- [ ] G6: SNAPSHOT payload + `process_snapshot` carry/surface folded-event identity + signatures\n      so compacted signed events still verify.\n- [ ] Key rotation via the version chain: events verify against the keys valid at their event\n      time (Lamport-scoped); rotation/revoke documented.\n- [ ] Jira identity mapping: `identity.jira-accountId` is the authoritative localâ†’accountId map;\n      reconciler resolves outbound assignee (and reporter via REST when Modify Reporter is\n      granted) by accountId, bootstraps/repairs via `/user/search`, and degrades gracefully\n      (`-1`/unassigned/bot-reporter) when email is hidden/unmatched â€” never hard-fails.\n- [ ] Jira inbound: reverse-resolve `accountId` â†’ identity; resolve-or-create an auto-upgrading\n      ghost identity for unmapped Jira users; external mapping keyed on provider stable id (not\n      email), provider-neutral so GitHub-Issues sync (`be74`) reuses it.\n- [ ] Docs: identity model, the three tiers, opt-in enforcement + CI pattern, fail-open/never-\n      reject semantics, the Jira accountId-mapping + Modify-Reporter constraint, and the\n      key-rotation limit/migration path.\n\n## Explicitly OUT of scope (follow-ons, file as separate linked tickets)\n\n- DSSE/in-toto/Sigstore keyless (\"Tier 2\") and any cross-org/transparency-log attestation\n  (different trust model) â€” track under the sibling security epic `8a1c`.\n- Active GitHub `ssh_signing_keys` cross-check / social-proof verification of `github-login`.\n- Full reconciler provider-generalization + GitHub Issues user sync (epic `be74`) â€” this epic\n  delivers the identity substrate + Jira mapping; broad provider refactor lands there.\n- Reporter sync where the project lacks Modify Reporter permission (documented degradation only).","title":"Authenticated identity â€” git-bug-model identity entity + SSHSIG signing + Jira accountId mapping"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1781930575423850001,"uuid":"e3c38e8b-eecc-40a0-be4a-dca490b6654d"}